    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a standalone factor addresses iterative convergence error distinct from discretization error in codes where solver iteration and mesh refinement are independently controllable. For the RANS steady-state simulations performed here, iterative residuals were driven below 1×10⁻⁶ for all equations at every operating point, and the distinction between solver iteration error and discretization error collapses to the discretization error factor already assessed above. ASME V&V 40 Table 2 guidance indicates this factor may be treated as not-applicable when iterative convergence is demonstrated to be negligible relative to discretization error, which is the case here (ratio < 0.1%). This factor is therefore not-applicable to this assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses the risk of incorrect model application by an end-user unfamiliar with the simulation tool. In this assessment the CFD model is developed and executed exclusively by the credibility assessment team — the same team responsible for the V&V activities — under a controlled analysis protocol with mandatory peer review of all simulation setups. There is no downstream hand-off of the model to a separate user population. Consequently, the organisational controls that motivate this factor are not present in this COU, and the factor is not-applicable per ASME V&V 40 §6.3 guidance that permits scoping-out factors whose risk drivers are absent from the use scenario."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty concerns the adequacy of the chosen turbulence closure and constitutive equations relative to the physical phenomena. For this MRL 2 assessment the model form (k-ω SST RANS with power-law hemolysis damage accumulation) is an industry-standard choice for centrifugal blood pump CFD that has been validated against experimental data in the output-comparison factor above. ASME V&V 40 Table 2 notes that at MRL 2 a separate model-form factor assessment is not required when the model form is established by the validation evidence already captured; the validation results subsume the model-form evidence. The factor is therefore not-applicable as a distinct credibility element at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model inputs uncertainty addresses variability in patient-specific or device-specific input parameters that propagate to QoI uncertainty. This COU is a deterministic worst-case identification study over a fixed set of five nominal operating points derived from the FDA experimental protocol; there is no patient population variability or manufacturing tolerance sweep in scope. Input parameter values are directly measured experimental quantities with documented traceability (flow meter ±1.5%, tachometer ±0.5%, viscometer ±2%). A formal uncertainty propagation analysis for model inputs is therefore not warranted at MRL 2 for this deterministic comparative study, and the factor is not-applicable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Test samples as a credibility factor addresses variability in physical test specimens used for validation — for example, unit-to-unit geometric variation across multiple manufactured pump housings. In this study a single FDA generic centrifugal pump specimen was used for all validation experiments, consistent with the FDA protocol design. The COU does not involve characterising device-to-device manufacturing variability; it concerns identifying worst-case operating conditions for a single nominal geometry. Sample-to-sample variability is therefore outside the scope of this COU, and this factor is not-applicable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters addresses the degree to which simulation input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) match those of the physical system when the simulation and validation domains differ. In this assessment the validation experiments were conducted on the same physical geometry and under boundary conditions directly matched to the simulation inputs (as documented under the test-conditions factor). There is no domain-shift between validation and COU environments that would require an equivalency argument. The factor is therefore not-applicable because the precondition for its use — a gap between validation and deployment input parameter spaces — does not exist in this COU."
    }
