  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-cpb-acceptance-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "rationale": "The CFD model of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump is accepted for the COU of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions under CPB conditions at MRL 2. Seven credibility factors were formally assessed: software quality assurance (Gradation 2 met), numerical code verification (Gradation 2 met), discretization error (Gradation 3 achieved, exceeding Gradation 2 requirement), test conditions (Gradation 2 met), output comparison (Gradation 2 met — RH index agreement within ±11%), relevance of QoIs (Gradation 2 met), and relevance of validation activities to the COU (Gradation 2 met). All assessed factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels; no shortfalls exist and no offset rationale is required. Six factors were determined not-applicable with documented rationale: numerical solver error (iterative convergence negligible relative to discretization error at residuals < 1e-6), use error (no downstream user population; controlled team execution), model form (subsumed by validation evidence at MRL 2), model inputs (deterministic nominal study; no patient or manufacturing variability in scope), test samples (single-specimen FDA protocol; no sample variability in COU scope), and equivalency of input parameters (no domain-shift between validation and deployment environments). The structured evidence base — comprising two independent validation results with uncertainty quantification, a three-level mesh convergence study, and full provenance back to the FDA experimental dataset and Morrison et al. (2017) — provides sufficient and coherent support for the claim that the CFD model correctly identifies worst-case hemolysis operating conditions with RH < 1. The acceptance decision is grounded in the complete evidence record with no unresolved shortfalls."
  },
